WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:29.959
The Penobscot Nation has been here, while I've heard tribal leaders say, for millennia,

00:00:30.120 --> 00:00:37.639
they called us nomads, but nomads just wander. We went with the seasons. The tribe used the river

00:00:37.639 --> 00:00:44.520
like its own highway, so that was our road system. And that's where our traditional fishing was.

00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:51.480
It was all kinds of fish, like sea lamprey. We ate sturgeon, striper bass. Everything that

00:00:51.480 --> 00:00:57.799
runs up the river now, those are our traditional fish. So that's why we look at her as a relative,

00:00:57.799 --> 00:01:08.360
a sister, someone that gives life. My name is Jan Paul. I work for the Penobscot Nation

00:01:08.360 --> 00:01:14.199
in their Department of Natural Resources, Water Quality. I was born and raised on Indian Island.

00:01:14.760 --> 00:01:21.800
I've lived here my entire life. Growing up on Indian Island was poor, but close-knitted.

00:01:21.800 --> 00:01:28.680
My mother and father ingrained in us a fear for the river, because she's so powerful that

00:01:29.320 --> 00:01:35.320
she would take you if you got too close. So when we were younger, we had that fear. But then,

00:01:36.040 --> 00:01:42.680
as I got older, you know, you could smell her sometimes. On the edge, it was stinky. And so,

00:01:42.680 --> 00:01:47.480
as I got this opportunity to work for the tribe, then that's when I started noticing,

00:01:47.480 --> 00:01:53.879
yeah, our river is really polluted. And I did my first summer. And that's when I saw an algae

00:01:53.879 --> 00:02:00.360
bloom. During the day, they come to the surface to get the light. So they're getting all their

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:06.839
oxygen from the sun. And then when the sun starts to go down, they sink to the bottom. They take

00:02:06.839 --> 00:02:13.479
all the oxygen out of the water column. So what that does is they put strain on the aquatic life,

00:02:13.479 --> 00:02:18.039
but especially the fish. So they won't be able to breathe, and so you'll see fish kills.

00:02:18.759 --> 00:02:24.520
When you see someone you love getting polluted, not by choice, but just by the air they breathe,

00:02:24.520 --> 00:02:30.119
or someone's putting something in your water, it just, it's heart-wrenching.

00:02:34.440 --> 00:02:39.000
But all the males above us now are gone. Once we were able to be

00:02:39.320 --> 00:02:47.720
viewed as people and started getting help from the United States, that's when we started

00:02:47.720 --> 00:02:53.240
taking care of her, in the sense that we started our water quality monitoring program.

00:02:58.279 --> 00:03:05.080
Our data was going on a piece of paper, and it would take years to get into our database.

00:03:05.080 --> 00:03:10.600
It was tough getting our data in, and tough getting it out. There's a story about me losing

00:03:10.600 --> 00:03:16.199
all my data sheets. The wind took them off my clipboard, and they went floating down the river.

00:03:17.399 --> 00:03:22.520
And you can't recreate data. Once you're there, it's going to be different because it's a flowing

00:03:22.520 --> 00:03:31.080
river. But then we went paperless. From the field, we checked in to what we call the workstation.

00:03:31.639 --> 00:03:36.279
From the workstation, and then we'd send it off to the lab so they could add their data in.

00:03:36.839 --> 00:03:43.000
And then from the lab, permanently stored in our database, which we use our studio to write

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:49.800
code to pull it out so we can run reports and do graphs and stuff like that. Open source tools

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:56.199
and POSIT help keep us fast and efficient in dealing with the health of the Penobscot River.

00:03:57.080 --> 00:04:02.360
Our data has showed the Department of Environmental Protection a couple of sections of the river

00:04:03.240 --> 00:04:08.520
is meeting a different classification, and so the upgrades were passed in 2019.

00:04:12.440 --> 00:04:19.320
My hopes for the river's future is that she's healthy, in the sense that when she's healthy,

00:04:19.320 --> 00:04:27.640
we're healthy. And so the healthier she is, the healthier we are as a people.

